# Version Control using Git and the Command Line

![](data:image/png;base64,)

To initialize git, type the following in command line -
`git init`

To add version control to our working directory , we need to add the working directory to a Staging Area.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

In the Staging Area you can pick and choose which files you want to commit.

Use the following command to see what's inside the staging area -
`git status`

In order to add files to the staging area so that you can track changes to it, type -
`git add chapter1.txt`
	where chapter1.txt is the file that you want to keep track of.

To add everything inside the current directory type -
`git add .`

To commit chapter1.txt under version control type -
`git commit -m "Complete Chapter 1"`

Use the -m flag to write commit messages. Commit message must be in present tense.

To see the commits that you've made, type -
`git log`

To check out what are the difference between the current version of a file and the last save point in our git repository , type -
`git diff chapter3.txt`

To rollback to previous saved version of the file we type -
`git checkout chapter3.txt`
